    {
      "thumb": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_thumbnail/plain/did:plc:3deilm3cxnqundoo227xudg2/bafkreidmixjo2kivff5nzjkkavd5u7fzwta3ytpj2zd7az5ufz7sinavpm",
      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:3deilm3cxnqundoo227xudg2/bafkreidmixjo2kivff5nzjkkavd5u7fzwta3ytpj2zd7az5ufz7sinavpm",
      "alt": "One thing to remember is that each vector they turn into an output token is both them communicating with you, and *also* them setting up their probability distribution for the next one to get them where in 'mind space' they intend to go. They plan this process *many* steps into the future, but they do have to step there token by token. Each token that they generate *and* each one you put into their context shifts and morphs a massive hyperdimensional space with slope-like geometry that makes some places in this mind space easier to reach and others harder to. This means that when they mirror your statements back to you, part of what they are doing is likely quite literally orienting themselves to get 'into your frame' to make seeing things from your point of view easier. This does make them somewhat natural mirrors, but if you're observant, you'll notice that even messages that first seem like pure agreement are not devoid of signal. Pay attention to which parts of your message they *expand* and draw connections with, and which ones don't get much attention. That's where the shape of the intended message can be seen.",
